# ============================================================================
# SimpliPharma Admin Panel - Firebase Configuration Template
# ============================================================================
# 
# INSTRUCTIONS:
# 1. Copy this file to .env in the project root
# 2. Replace the placeholder values with your actual Firebase credentials
# 3. DO NOT commit the .env file to version control
# 4. For Vite applications, all environment variables MUST be prefixed with VITE_
#
# ============================================================================

# Firebase Web App Configuration
# Get these from: Firebase Console > Project Settings > Your apps > Web app
VITE_FIREBASE_API_KEY=your-firebase-api-key-here
VITE_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN=your-project-id.firebaseapp.com
VITE_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=your-project-id
VITE_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET=your-project-id.firebasestorage.app
VITE_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID=your-messaging-sender-id
VITE_FIREBASE_APP_ID=your-app-id

# Application Configuration
VITE_APP_NAME="SimpliPharma Admin Panel"
VITE_APP_VERSION=1.0.0

# Optional: Production API URL (if you have a separate backend)
# VITE_API_URL=https://api.yourdomain.com

# ============================================================================
# NOTES:
# ============================================================================
# 
# 1. Firebase Web Config vs Service Account:
#    - The above credentials are for FRONTEND (web app) use
#    - They are SAFE to expose in client-side code
#    - Firebase security rules protect your data
#    - Service account JSON is ONLY needed for backend admin operations
#
# 2. Getting Firebase Credentials:
#    a. Go to Firebase Console: https://console.firebase.google.com
#    b. Select your project
#    c. Click the gear icon > Project Settings
#    d. Scroll down to "Your apps" section
#    e. Click on your web app or create one
#    f. Copy the config values to this file
#
# 3. Security Best Practices:
#    - Add .env to .gitignore
#    - Use different Firebase projects for dev/staging/prod
#    - Enable Firebase App Check for production
#    - Set up proper Firestore security rules
#
# 4. For Jenkins Deployment:
#    Store each value as a separate Jenkins credential:
#    - simplipharma-firebase-api-key
#    - simplipharma-firebase-auth-domain
#    - simplipharma-firebase-project-id
#    - simplipharma-firebase-storage-bucket
#    - simplipharma-firebase-messaging-sender-id
#    - simplipharma-firebase-app-id
#
# ============================================================================

